<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   NBC Cable Channel to Offer Incentives
   To Operators to Get Them to Carry It
   ----
   By Kevin Goldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   GE CVC
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- National Broadcasting Co.'s Consumer News and
Business Channel, struggling to gain acceptance in an
overcrowded field of programming choices, will begin offering
cable operators a cash incentive to carry its service.
   At the National Cable Television Association conference
here, CNBC said it will pay $3 a subscriber to cable
operators who commit 75% of their subscriber base to carry
the 24-hour channel by July 1, 1991. The deal is being
offered until August 15.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   CNBC's unusual move comes as the overpopulated cable field
is becoming even more cramped. A number of other new "basic
services," which are offered as part of the standard
programming package on a cable subscriber's bill, are vying
here for the attention of cable operators.
   Although the newcomers are optimistic about the chances
for acceptance, there's a shortage of channel capacity in the
cable industry at present, and some cable operators are
putting expansion plans on hold until the industry has a
better idea of what new regulations Congress may slap on the
industry. Even the industry's most powerful players are
having a tough time: Time Warner Inc.'s Comedy Channel and
Viacom Inc.'s Ha] Channel are discussing a merger because of
the difficulty in selling cable operators on the idea of two
comedy networks.
   Among the new channels being hawked at the cable
convention are the Career Television Network, or CTVN, which
will program tips on how to find jobs; the Cowboy Channel,
which boasts singer Willie Nelson as its chairman; and the
Golden American Network, which is targeted at older viewers
and plans shows such as "Satellite Bingo" and a "Dating Game"
for people over 50 years old.
   There is also a "How-To" channel, as well as "Sci-Fi,"
which hopes to get off the ground by year end. Add to that
two channels programming legal shows and headline grabbing
trials.
   Each programmer hopes to launch with at least five million
subscribers. That's a far cry from the most recent successful
launch, Turner Network Television, from Turner Broadcasting
System Inc. The 24-hour channel, which features films and
made-for-TV movies, began Oct. 3, 1988, with approximately 17
million subscribers and now boasts 45 million.
   Thomas Rogers, president of CNBC, said the service,
launched last August, has 16 million subscribers, a level
that he characterized as "way ahead of schedule." Mr. Rogers
said the payment to cable operators, which he labeled as a
"marketing incentive plan," was being done to "accelerate
distribution." NBC's partner in CNBC is Cablevision Systems
Corp., an owner of cable systems and cable program networks.
NBC is a unit of General Electric Co.
   CNBC's primary competitor, Financial News Network, which
has been on the air since November 1981, has 33.5 million
subscibers, said Gil Faccio, FNN senior vice president of
affiliate relations. Mr. Faccio said the service has no plans
to pay cable operators for subscribers. "We believe our
product should be product-motivated, not financially
motivated," he said.
   While the major broadcast networks pay TV stations to be
affiliates and to carry network programs, it's usually the
cable operators who pay programming suppliers for the right
to carry a channel in the cable industry. Such payments are
determined by the number of subscribers a cable system has.
Only rarely has a cable channel paid cable operators for
space on their system.
   For example, American Broadcasting Co., prior to its
acquisition by Capital Cities Communications Inc., and
Westinghouse Electric Co.'s Group W unit paid cable operators
six years ago to carry Satellite News Channel, an attempt to
compete in the all-news arena with Turner's Cable News
Network. The Satellite News Channel was unable to compete
effectively with CNN, which eventually bought it out and
folded it.
   Mr. Rogers dismissed the charge that CNBC was desperate to
sign on cable operators. "This shows the confidence our
owners have in the service," he said, sitting in an elaborate
CNBC booth on the convention floor. "This shows we're here to
stay."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900523-0158
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900523-0158.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Federal Express
   Stock Plunges
   On Growth Data
   ---
   Lower April Volume Hurts
   Chances for Turnaround;
   Earnings Estimates Cut
   ----
   By Peter Waldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   FDX ABF
</CO>
<IN>
AIR FREIGHT (AIF)
</IN>
<LP>
   A sharp and unexpected drop in Federal Express Corp.'s
shipment growth in April sent the company's stock tumbling
almost 10% as investors lost patience with the struggling
air-express carrier.
   Though Federal Express has posted year-to-year earnings
declines in each of the past five quarters, industry analysts
-- encouraged by recent statements by the Memphis,
Tenn.-based company -- had expected a solid turnaround in the
fourth quarter ending May 31. Since December, investors have
bid up the price of the company's shares about 25%, to the
mid-$50 range, despite disappointing operating results.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Late Monday, however, after the markets closed, Federal
Express disclosed more bad news that seemed to crush hopes
for an early turnaround: The company said shipment volume of
express packages and documents rose just 10.1% in April from
a year earlier, a steep dropoff from volume growth of 16% to
20% in previous quarters.
   Because of the low volume of shipments, a company
spokesman said, Federal Express is now "pessimistic" that it
can match or exceed year-ago net income of $41 million, or 78
cents a share.
   In heavy New York Stock Exchange composite trading,
Federal Express tumbled $5.125 to $47.
   "There's great conceptuals here -- there's great long-term
potential -- but there has to come a time when you start
seeing some results," said Kevin Murphy, an analyst with
Morgan Stanley. Mr. Murphy was one of the industry analysts
who had been touting Federal Express's stock loudest before
yesterday, when he lowered his fourth-quarter earnings
estimate for the company about 34%, to 65 cents a share from
98 cents a share.
   "The script has changed," he said.
   The Federal Express spokesman attributed April's
lower-than-expected volume growth to a price increase April
1. Federal Express's average daily volume of express packages
and documents increased in April to 1.3 million from 1.2
million a year earlier.
   The spokesman also said Federal Express's heavyweight
cargo -- the business it entered upon acquiring Tiger
International Corp. last year -- dropped to an average daily
volume of 2.8 million pounds in April from 3.3 million pounds
a day in March. He cited weaker-than-expected exports from
Asia, particularly textiles and toys.
   Analysts said Federal Express's lackluster shipment growth
in the express-package market indicates that rival Airborne
Freight Corp. may be winning business away from the
much-larger Federal Express. Airborne has been targeting
large-volume express customers with lowball prices, according
to James Parker, an analyst with Robinson Humphrey Co. in
Atlanta, a strategy that has proven particularly successful
in the wake of Federal's price increases, he said. Airborne's
volume grew 35% in April, Mr. Parker estimates.
   "What really scares everyone is the possibility that
Federal's business will remain soft and Airborne's will
remain strong, prompting Federal to become very aggressive on
pricing and start another price war," said Mr. Parker. "A
price war could negate major earnings improvements" across
the industry for several more quarters.
   Mr. Parker slashed his projections of Federal Express's
fourth-quarter earnings to 62 cents a share from 92 cents a
share. He also revised his profit expectations for Federal
for fiscal 1991 to $3 a share from $4 a share.
   "This was the quarter when they were supposed to begin
putting it all together," said Paul Schlesinger, an analyst
with Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp., who cut
his fourth-quarter profit projections for Federal Express to
60 cents a share from 78 cents a share. "I'm not at all
confident that they can even make 60 cents a share," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
