<HL>
   RTZ Unit's Accord
   With Unions May
   Sway Other Talks
   ----
   By Keith Alexander
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR U.RTZ PD AR
</CO>
<IN>
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
</IN>
<LP>
   A tentative labor contract covering 2,000 workers at
Kennecott Corp.'s Bingham Canyon mine in Utah could set a
precedent for future labor negotiations in the nation's
copper industry.
   Kennecott agreed to a new three-year labor accord,
effective July 1, that will boost pay about 20% for workers
at its mine in Salt Lake City.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say the partial restoration of past lost wages
agreed to in the new contract is likely to set a pattern as
rivals Phelps Dodge Corp. and Asarco Inc. begin negotiating
contracts later this year. Labor pacts covering 3,550 workers
at Kennecott, a unit of London-based RTZ Corp., Phelps Dodge
and Asarco all expire June 30.
   The new contract reflects better times in the copper
industry, which was virtually at a standstill when the
current pact was negotiated in 1986. At that time,
Kennecott's Bingham Canyon site, the nation's largest
open-pit copper mine, was closed. The mine was reopened in
July 1986 when the union agreed to concessions.
   Kennecott has since undergone extensive restructuring,
mirroring similar actions by other U.S. copper producers. It
sold four mines, closed another and only has one copper site
left at Bingham Canyon, in addition to gold, silver and lead
properties elsewhere. Kennecott was acquired by RTZ last
year.
   The Kennecott contract covers members of the United
Steelworkers union, the bargaining agent, as well as 12 other
smaller unions. Members will vote tomorrow on the accord,
which has been in negotiation for about a month and a half.
   In the first year of the contract, beginning July 1, wages
will increase to about $12 an hour from roughly $10
currently. The present contract lowered average hourly wages
to about $10 from roughly $13.75 in 1986 when the
concessionary pact took effect.
   Union officials declined to provide further details on the
wage settlement pending the worker vote. However, wage
increases are expected to average about 50 cents annually
during the second and third years, according to published
reports.
   Wayne Holland, a USW sub-district director in Salt Lake
City, predicted employee ratification, though he said workers
had expected about 50 cents more an hour. "We were looking
for all that was given to us in 1986," Mr. Holland said,
referring to full restoration of the givebacks that Kennecott
won then.
   In addition to the basic-wage package, Kennecott agreed to
lower the health-insurance deductible to $100 for each
person, or $300 for each family. The agreement also provides
for an increase in pension benefit coverage, which wasn't
disclosed, as well as a $3,000 signing bonus for each worker
to be paid within 60 days after the contract is ratified.
   Don Babinchak, who represented Salt Lake City-based
Kennecott in the labor talks, called the contract an
"excellent settlement for our employees."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900523-0130
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900523-0130.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Ratings
   For Citicorp
   Cut by Moody's
   ---
   Downgrade Involves Debt
   Of $31 Billion; Reserves,
   Capital Levels Are Cited
   ----
   By Robert Guenther
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   CCI
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
BANKS (BNK)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Moody's Investors Service Inc. lowered its
credit ratings on Citicorp, including its commercial paper,
citing comparatively low reserve and capital levels and a
rising number of problem loans.
   The move, which follows a similar downgrading by Standard
&amp; Poor's Corp. last month, affects an estimated $31 billion
in long-term and short-term debt. S&amp;P had affirmed its rating
on Citicorp's commercial paper, a regular source of funding
for the nation's largest banking company.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Moody's dropped its ratings on senior debt to single-A-3
from single-A-1 and on commercial paper to Prime-2 from
Prime-1. Subordinated debt and preferred were reduced to
Baa-1 from single-A-2 and from single-A-3 to single-A-2,
respectively. Moody's said a two-notch reduction in a rating
is unusual.
   The Prime-1 rating on the short-term deposits and letters
of credit of its flagship, Citibank, were confirmed. However,
long-term deposits and long-term letters of credit were
reduced to single-A-1 from double-A-2.
   It is unclear whether investors have fully discounted the
downgrading. When the Moody's review was announced in April,
the pricing on Citicorp paper rose relative to other issuers.
Though Citicorp remains an investment-grade debtor, the lower
rating on its commercial paper will make the bank's paper
off-limits for some institutional investors.
   Since the review was announced, Citicorp has downplayed
the significance of a downgrading, noting that the company
satisfies only about 2% of its funding needs through the
commercial-paper market. In addition, the bank has no plans
to issue long-term debt.
   The company has defended its reserves and capital
positions, emphasizing its unique global character and its
rigorous underwriting standards in arguing why it shouldn't
be held to the standards of other banks.
   Nevertheless, the downgrading, which comes on the heels of
similar reviews for dozens of other banks, could crimp
Citicorp when it raises funds in the future.
   The announcement was made after the close of trading. In
composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Citicorp
was down 12.5 cents at $23.75 a share.
   Kenneth J.H. Pinkes, a Moody's vice president, said,
"They're still a strong company, but they have a low level of
capital for a bank with their old rating. The company has
always operated with a thin margin of safety, while pursuing
multiple business opportunities. There isn't much of a
cushion."
   At the end of last year, Citicorp's nonperforming loans
and those loans 90 days or more past due amounted to 6.6% of
total loans. Meanwhile, its reserves totaled 44% of its
problem loans.
   By comparison, the averages for U.S. banks with more than
$30 billion in assets are a 4.5% level of problem loans and
reserves totaling 89% of such loans. BankAmerica Corp.'s loan
problems, for instance, were 5.8% of its loans, and its
reserves stood at 70% of problem portfolio.
   Nevertheless, Moody's said that while Citicorp's
real-estate portfolio is geographically diverse and while its
underwriting standards appear to be sound, it is vulnerable
to the deteriorating national real-estate market.
   In a statement, Citicorp said, "We're very disappointed
with Moody's action. We don't expect any significant increase
in overall funding costs. Increasing securitization of assets
has substantially decreased Citicorp's use of long-term debt,
while deposit growth has reduced commercial paper to 2% of
funding needs. Citibank retains the highest short-term
deposit rating."
   As previously indicated, Citicorp said it will rebuild
capital throughout 1990 from retained earnings and sale of
non-strategic assets as well as what it called "vigorous
asset management."
   Citicorp pointed out that the Aaa ratings on its most
recent offering of securities backed by credit-card
receivables aren't affected. Ratings on some mortgage-backed
pass-throughs were lowered one notch. Additionally, several
tranches of multiclass mortgage securities were reaffirmed.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   MOODY'S INVESTORS SERVICE Inc. lowered the rating on
Citicorp's preferred stock to single-A-3 from single-A-2. In
yesterday's edition, the reduction was misstated.
   (WSJ May 24, 1990)
</TEXT>
