   Japan Export Ship Orders Rise
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
SHIPBUILDERS OF COMMERCIAL SHIPS (SHP)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Japanese shipbuilders signed export contracts to
build 25 ships with a combined weight of 1.1 million metric
tons in April, up 78% from 589,725 metric tons a year
earlier, the Japan Ship Exporters' Association reported
Tuesday.
   In March, by comparison, the shipbuilding industry
contracted to export 16 vessels, weighing 827,800 metric
gross tons.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The association spokesman traced the sharp year-on-year
rise to comparatively sluggish contracts last year when an
increase in export insurance fees imposed at the beginning of
April 1989 caused a large number of ship buyers to rush their
orders ahead of the deadline. In March 1989, ship export
contracts rose to a high of 1.5 million tons.
</TEXT>
