<HL>
   Technology:
   Two U.S. Firms, Soviets
   Forming Biotech Venture
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MENLO PARK, Calif. -- A Silicon Valley venture capital
firm said it is forming an unusual alliance with a Soviet
partner aimed at developing an alternative approach toward
genetic engineering.
   The alliance will include Sierra Ventures, the venture
capital firm, the Institute of Protein Research, a Soviet
biotechnology research institute near Moscow, and closely
held RiboGene Inc., a California biotech company. Sierra
Ventures called the arrangement "the first Soviet-American
biotech start-up."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The aim is to develop a technique for producing proteins
without using living cells. Current techniques involve
inserting genes into bacterial or mammalian cells.
Identifying single proteins from hundreds or thousands of
other proteins in such cells can be tedious and
time-consuming.
   Sierra Ventures said the Soviet institute is swapping
technology for a 15% stake in RiboGene and is also obtaining
a 49% stake in a related joint venture. Sierra Ventures said
it plans to invest as much as $2 million in RiboGene and the
joint firm.
   The venture arises out of separate research by scientists
at RiboGene and at the Soviet institute. The Soviet research
was somewhat more advanced than that of the U.S. firm. "They
had also been skillful in patenting their discoveries
world-wide," said Petri Vainio, a Sierra Ventures principal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900523-0043
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900523-0043.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Harken Energy Clears
   Stock-Rights Offering
   To Raise New Capital
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   HEC
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Harken Energy Corp. said its directors approved
a rights offering to raise more than $40 million to repay
debt, pay for capital expenditures and provide working
capital to two of the company's subsidiaries.
   Harken, an energy concern, apparently wants to raise the
funds in part to recapitalize its Harken Marketing Co. unit,
which at March 31 was in violation of certain bank covenants.
However, Harken said that Harken Marketing's bank group has
agreed to waive those covenants until July 31 if Harken and
Harken Marketing agree to make a $15 million principal
payment on its $76.3 million in bank debt.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under an agreement reached earlier this week, undisclosed
Harken stockholders have agreed to loan Harken Marketing $26
million, of which $15 million will be used to pay the bank
principal and the remaining amount will be used for working
capital. As part of that agreement, the stockholders will be
able to use their loan to buy shares under the rights
offerings.
   The energy concern said that under the rights offering, it
would allow its shareholders to buy stock in Harken
Marketing, a gasoline wholesaler and retailer that had gross
profit of $9.1 million on revenue of $247 million for the
first quarter, and Tejas Power Corp., a natural gas gathering
and marketing concern that had first-quarter operating profit
of $2.5 million on revenue of about $27 million.
   Separately, Harken Energy said it had a net loss for the
first quarter of $2.2 million, or 10 cents a share, compared
with a loss of $1.2 million, or six cents a share, last year.
Revenue increased almost 10%, to $279.7 million from $254.4
million last year.
</TEXT>
