<LP>
   NIKKEI PUT WARRANTS' potential gains in the event of a 30%
drop in the Nikkei index of 225 Tokyo stocks were understated
by 100 percentage points in a story and an accompanying table
in yesterday's edition because of a miscalculation. For
example, in the case of the Denmark put, the gain from the
May 18 level would be 148% (instead of 48%); in the case of
the newer PaineWebber put, the gain would be 242% (not 142%).
   (See: "Putting Latest Nikkei-Index Play to Test" -- WSJ
May 22, 1990)
</LP>
<TEXT>
   ---
   GREYHOUND LINES INC., a unit of Dallas-based GLI Holding
Co., offered to redeem about $191 million in face amount of
debt for about $86 million in cash. The figures were
incorrectly stated in yesterday's edition.
   (See: "Greyhound Lines Hopes to Redeem Portion of Debt" --
WSJ May 22, 1990)
   ---
   CARLTON COMMUNICATIONS shares declined 25 pence to 515
pence Monday in trading on London's stock exchange. The
decline was misstated in yesterday's edition.
   (See: "World Markets: Taiwan Index Drops 4th Time in a Row
to Low For 15-Months; Equities Off in Frankfurt, Tokyo" --
WSJ May 22, 1990)
   ---
   CLARENCE GONSALVES is a former manager of the now-defunct
Western Services Department, Pomona, Calif., of Northrop
Corp.'s Precision Products division, and Howard Hyde is a
former senior engineer of the department. Recent editions
mistakenly said that the Precision Products division,
Norwood, Mass., was the unit that closed.
   (See: ""Ex-Northrop Official Gets Prison Sentence Of One
Year, One Day" -- WSJ May 21, 1990 and "Ex-Northrop Aide
Sentenced to Prison in Falsifying Tests" -- WSJ May 18, 1990)
   ---
   COMMERZBANK OVERSEAS FINANCE N.V. offered 150 billion lira
of 12 5/8% Eurobonds priced at 101.4 to yield 12.70% less
fees. In yesterday's edition the denomination of the
Eurobonds was omitted.
   (See: "New Securities Issues" -- WSJ May 22, 1990)
