<HL>
   Freddie Mac Plans to Buy
   Five-Year Balloon Loans
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   FRE CCI
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. plans to start
swapping, in negotiated transactions, five-year balloon loans
with monthly payments based on a 30-year repayment
reschedule.
   The loans are attractive to starter-home buyers, military
families and others who plan to stay in a house for fewer
than five years. Freddie Mac expects investors to find
mortgage participation certificates backed by the loans
attractive because of their shorter duration and more
predictable maturity.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The interest rate on the loans is lower than rates for
regular 30-year loans. After five years, a borrower can repay
the loan, extend it, or refinance at a new fixed rate for 25
years. New rates under the extension or refinancing options
will be set at half a percentage point over the current
Freddie Mac 60-day required net yield. The rate increase is
capped at five percentage points over the original loan.
   Freddie Mac, based in Reston, Va., is a
government-sponsored, publicly traded company that operates a
secondary market for mortgages, buying loans from lenders,
packaging them into securities and selling them to investors.
   Separately, Freddie Mac said it bought $131 million in
loans on multifamily properties from Citicorp Mortgage Inc.,
which exchanged the loans for the same amount in Freddie Mac
multifamily mortgage participation certificates. Freddie Mac
said the 630 loans are secured by apartment buildings, mostly
small buildings with five to 12 units, in the Chicago area.
   The company said it bought a $37 million multifamily loan
-- the largest it ever purchased -- from Globe Mortgage Co.
of Hackensack, N.J. The loan is for rental housing in
suburban Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900523-0004
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900523-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Martech Expects Net
   For Fiscal 1990 to Lag
   Anticipated Levels
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   MUSA
</CO>
<LP>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska -- Martech USA Inc. said it expects
lower-than-anticipated fiscal 1990 revenue and profit because
of reduced work associated with the continuing cleanup of
last year's Exxon Valdez oil spill.
   Martech, an oil field-cleanup and marine-services firm,
said it expects to report revenue for the fiscal year ending
August 31 in the range of $52 million to $55 million, and net
income for the year approximating $1 a share, or about $9.4
million. The figure is higher than year-earlier results, but
less than the $65 million in annual revenue that Martech had
anticipated earlier this year and below earnings of $1.10 to
$1.17 a share anticipated by some analysts. The outlook
basically assumes roughly flat earnings and revenues for the
second half compared with year-earlier levels.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Martech said the revised outlook assumed no further
revenue contribution from Exxon Corp. from work on the oil
spill, which accounted for more than 80% of the company's
second-half revenue last year. Martech said Exxon plans to
increasingly rely on bio-remediation techniques in completing
the cleanup, which is much less labor-intensive than the
process used last year.
   Martech emphasized that it is still bidding for certain
Exxon contracts on the spill and still may realize additional
revenue from it. A spokesman said the latest estimate was
"almost a worst-case scenario."
   Martech became publicly held in December. While the
company recently changed its fiscal year, for the 12 months
ended August 31, 1989, it had profit of $7.7 million, or 64
cents a share, on revenue of $41.1 million.
   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, Martech
closed at $11.50, down 50 cents.
</TEXT>
